Statement when visiting/ travelling to VesselThere may arise situations where Shore (office) staffs have little option but to respond to queries from the media for e.g., when theyhave been sent to attend to the ship after a incident etc. If this occurs, they must refer the media to the company’s Media/Communications team. Below is a sample statement: <Quote> “I am xxxx (name of the superintendent) from the Executive Offshore, the ship manager of the vessel ABCD (name of the vessel). Iam not in the position to answer your questions at the moment. You may contact our Media/ Communications team for informationabout the incident.” <Unquote>7.9.5COMMUNICATING WITH THE MEDIA1. The following are the advantages of limiting media contact with the Master: a. One point of contact minimizes the possibility of conflicting information b. The Master is the senior most person in the vessel and the media will accord greater credibility of statements made by him; c. The Master, through the Media/ Communications team will be able to collect and present relevant facts regarding the incident andthe development of the response; d. The master will have access to feedback and guidance from the Media/ Communications team on how best to respond to queries2. In case media still proceeds with talking to the company representative and/or crew, they should: a. Be honest b. Be brief and to the point c. Stick to confirmed facts and avoid speculations d. Not volunteer unsolicited information3. The following are some examples of the questions media may ask: a. Any casualties? b. What’s being done to minimize damage to the environment? c. Danger to wildlife and what’s being done? d. How long before the crisis can be brought under control? e. Master’s biographical profile f. The number of crew on board, their nationality etc. g. Vessel’s survey status and other information such as cargo, charterers, destinations h. Has the vessel been involved in other incidents in the past? i. Has the Company been involved in other incidents in the past? j. The role of Executive Offshore in this incident. k. What is the core business of Executive Offshore and what is the fleet profile.4. A brief list of do’s and don’ts when dealing with the media:Do’sDon’tsExpress concern about the incident and its falloutNever be flippant or humorous in communications with mediapersonnelBe honest and truthful when describing the incident or relatedissuesDon’t try to conceal facts or say ‘No comment’Be factual in your statementsNever speculate on the cause of an incident or its likely impactBe brief and to the point in all communications.Don’t leave out important detailsBe clear and specific about what action the Company is taking todeal with the incidentDon’t criticize other agencies or organizations that are involved in theincident or its responseDon’t invent/ speculate on an answerDon’t become antagonistic towards the questioner7.10MEDIA HOLDING STATEMENTS7.10.1MEDIA HOLDING STATEMENT - OPTION 1(On (The ((
